Blood tests are taken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peripheral blood smear","Whole-body low-dose computed tomography","Serum parathyroid hormone","Serum protein electrophoresis","Bone marrow biopsy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with constitutional symptoms (fatigue, night sweats, weight loss), bony tenderness, hypercalcaemia and normocytic anaemia. This constellation of findings is highly suspicious for multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it can identify the presence of a monoclonal paraprotein, which is diagnostic for multiple myeloma. This test is readily available, non-invasive, and provides crucial diagnostic information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum parathyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E measurement would be appropriate if primary hyperparathyroidism was suspected. While hyperparathyroidism is the most common cause of hypercalcaemia in the general population, the presence of constitutional symptoms, anaemia, and bony tenderness makes multiple myeloma more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral blood smear\u003C/strong\u003E may show rouleaux formation in multiple myeloma, but this finding is neither sensitive nor specific. It would not be the most helpful next investigation in establishing the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhole-body low-dose computed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E has largely replaced traditional skeletal survey for detecting and monitoring osteolytic lesions in multiple myeloma. However, imaging should be performed after confirming the diagnosis with protein studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E provides definitive diagnosis by demonstrating clonal plasma cells. However, it is an invasive procedure that should be performed after less invasive testing has suggested the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnostic workup for multiple myeloma typically begins with serum protein electrophoresis, followed by serum free light chains and immunofixation. If these suggest multiple myeloma, then imaging and bone marrow biopsy are performed to confirm the diagnosis and assess disease burden.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Constitutional symptoms and bony tenderness require urgent investigation for multiple myeloma","Serum protein electrophoresis is the appropriate first-line investigation for suspected multiple myeloma","Whole-body low-dose CT has replaced skeletal survey for imaging in multiple myeloma"],"references":["Minisola S, Pepe J, Piemonte S, et al. The diagnosis and management of hypercalcaemia. BMJ 2015; 350h2723. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26037642/","Cowan AJ, Green DJ, Kwok M, Lee S, Coffey DG, Holmberg LA, et al. Diagnosis and Management of Multiple Myeloma: A Review. JAMA. 2022;327(5):464-77. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2788522"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"5"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"12819"},{"type":"media","id":"12820"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"12819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12819"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b6b6191-d8d7-4f5a-8676-9595261db2f4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b6b6191-d8d7-4f5a-8676-9595261db2f4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":198}},{"type":"media","id":"12820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12820"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https:/